{"questionId":"9483","questionHtml":"<p>local maximum points;</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>graphical or tabular evidence that <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"n\"> <mi>n</mi> </math></span> has been systematically varied&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em>eg</em> <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"n\"> <mi>n</mi> </math></span>&nbsp;= 2, 0 local maximum point and 1 local minimum point</p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"n\"> <mi>n</mi> </math></span>&nbsp;= 4, 1 local maximum points and 2 local minimum points</p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"n\"> <mi>n</mi> </math></span>&nbsp;= 6, 2 local maximum points and 3 local minimum points&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>&nbsp;(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{{n - 2}}{2}\"> <mfrac> <mrow> <mi>n</mi> <mo>−</mo> <mn>2</mn> </mrow> <mn>2</mn> </mfrac> </math></span> local maximum points&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9483","referenceCode":"SPM.3.AHL.TZ0.2d.i","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"local maximum points;","paper":"3","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"d.i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.6—Differentiating polynomials n E Q. Chain, product and quotient rules","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.9—Reciprocal trig ratios and their pythagorean identities. Inverse circular functions"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}